This research examines the inherent problem of reproducibility in digital art and creates a device-integrated visual generation method using electronic paper, along with a system called “createdAt:”.

Since digital data can be perfectly replicated without degradation, it leads to a weakening of uniqueness and singularity in art. NFT technology gained popularity as a method to overcome this problem, but it was due to external factors and did not fundamentally change the internal structure.

This research attempts to solve this problem from three perspectives and creates a digital art generation device based on its design philosophy. First, the materialization of digital art works using electronic paper. Second, the elimination of the artist's intent by directly using environmental variables for drawing. Third, the transparency of the relationship between the generation process and the environment.

We created a portable A4-sized device with a Raspberry Pi and a 7.5-inch electronic paper as the main components. It generates geometric patterns based on environmental information and displays them on the electronic paper. Its portability allows for generation in various environments, and by not leaving the generated data within the device, we explored the materialization and uniqueness of digital art works.

This system makes the generation and presentation of digital works and their surrounding environment inseparable, demonstrating the potential for new digital art that intrinsically possesses tangibility and uniqueness.
